6
00:02:51,631 --> 00:02:57,512
"Lend yourself to others,
but give yourself to yourself."
— Montaigne

7
00:03:01,182 --> 00:03:08,064
A CAFÉ — NANA WANTS TO GIVE UP —
PAUL — THE PINBALL MACHINE

8
00:03:12,569 --> 00:03:14,696
Do you really like the guy?

9
00:03:16,114 --> 00:03:18,032
I don't know.

10
00:03:18,491 --> 00:03:20,535
I wonder
what I was even thinking.

11
00:03:20,702 --> 00:03:22,620
Does he have more money
than me?

12
00:03:22,787 --> 00:03:24,706
What do you care?

13
00:03:25,874 --> 00:03:27,750
What do you care?

14
00:03:34,299 --> 00:03:35,967
Something bothering you?

15
00:03:36,134 --> 00:03:40,138
No, I just wanted to deliver
that line a specific way.

16
00:03:40,597 --> 00:03:43,933
I didn't know
the best way to say it.

17
00:03:44,309 --> 00:03:48,146
Or I did know,
but I don't anymore.

18
00:03:48,646 --> 00:03:52,984
Just when I should know, too.
Doesn't that ever happen to you?

19
00:03:53,234 --> 00:03:56,404
Don't you ever talk
about anything but yourself?

20
00:03:56,946 --> 00:03:58,740
You're horrible.

21
00:04:00,617 --> 00:04:03,870
I'm not horrible, Nana.
I'm sad.

22
00:04:04,787 --> 00:04:08,249
I'm not sad, Paul.
I'm horrible.

23
00:04:08,750 --> 00:04:11,753
Don't talk nonsense.
This isn't a stage.

24
00:04:13,296 --> 00:04:18,259
You never do as I ask, but you
always want me to do what you want.

25
00:04:19,177 --> 00:04:21,763
Anyway, I'm fed up.
I want to die.

26
00:04:21,930 --> 00:04:24,515
- Is that so?
- Yes, that's so.

27
00:04:24,682 --> 00:04:26,684
More nonsense.

28
00:04:27,602 --> 00:04:32,190
It's exhausting loving you.
I always have to beg.

29
00:04:33,066 --> 00:04:34,943
I exist too.

30
00:04:35,109 --> 00:04:38,112
You say I'm cruel,
but you're the cruel one.

31
00:04:48,790 --> 00:04:53,002
Why do you say that? It isn't true.
You mean Sunday evening?

32
00:04:53,962 --> 00:04:55,546
You know very well when.

33
00:04:55,672 --> 00:04:58,508
I begged you
to introduce me to that man.

34
00:04:58,633 --> 00:05:00,969
You did it on purpose.

35
00:05:01,135 --> 00:05:02,679
Yes, I did.

36
00:05:02,845 --> 00:05:05,014
You're pathetic.

37
00:05:07,100 --> 00:05:10,311
If we started over,
I'd just cheat on you again.

38
00:05:10,478 --> 00:05:12,146
Don't say that.

39
00:05:17,318 --> 00:05:18,736
Don't say that.

40
00:05:18,903 --> 00:05:20,154
It's true.

41
00:05:20,279 --> 00:05:24,826
I thought it was important
we should meet, but I don't anymore.

42
00:05:25,535 --> 00:05:28,663
We might have
got together again.

43
00:05:28,830 --> 00:05:31,916
But the more we talk,
the less the words mean.

44
00:05:33,209 --> 00:05:37,338
Anyway, if I make it on the stage,
it won't be thanks to you.

45
00:05:37,797 --> 00:05:39,882
Acting isn't everything.

46
00:05:40,049 --> 00:05:42,260
Not you too!
Why do you say that?

47
00:05:42,427 --> 00:05:45,179
If it's what I want,
why should you mind?

48
00:05:45,346 --> 00:05:48,016
I might be discovered
someday.

49
00:05:58,192 --> 00:06:00,403
Yes, you mustn't give up.

50
00:06:00,653 --> 00:06:03,031
I haven't given up music.

51
00:06:03,156 --> 00:06:06,993
Not like your English lessons.
You were never really interested.

52
00:06:07,118 --> 00:06:09,037
I'm not giving up.

53
00:06:09,162 --> 00:06:11,873
In fact, that guy's going
to take pictures of me.

54
00:06:12,832 --> 00:06:15,084
Maybe I'll get into the movies.

55
00:06:15,543 --> 00:06:17,503
That'll be the day.

56
00:06:17,837 --> 00:06:20,214
You're horrible, Paul.

57
00:06:28,431 --> 00:06:30,725
You're horrible, Paul.

58
00:06:32,226 --> 00:06:35,313
You really are.
It's always the same.

59
00:06:35,855 --> 00:06:40,693
You say you love me,
but you don't consider me special.

60
00:06:41,819 --> 00:06:46,908
I hardly love you anymore,
but I still consider you special.

61
00:06:47,408 --> 00:06:51,537
Why do you say things like that?
I think we're all the same.

62
00:06:52,288 --> 00:06:55,249
You don't approve of me
looking for work?

63
00:06:55,583 --> 00:06:58,961
It suits you even less
than all the rest.

64
00:06:59,128 --> 00:07:02,423
Anyway, you're leaving me
because I'm poor.

65
00:07:02,590 --> 00:07:05,051
When all's said and done, maybe.

66
00:07:06,427 --> 00:07:09,222
Have you got the pictures
you mentioned on the phone?

67
00:07:10,640 --> 00:07:14,811
I forgot them. They'll be ready
at the end of the week.

68
00:07:16,270 --> 00:07:18,981
Is he all right?
Is he eating well?

69
00:07:19,148 --> 00:07:22,527
He had an earache,
but the doctor said it was nothing.

70
00:07:22,693 --> 00:07:25,154
What's your job at Pathé-Marconi?

71
00:07:25,321 --> 00:07:27,281
I sell records.

72
00:07:29,117 --> 00:07:31,244
Can you lend me 2,000 francs?

73
00:07:32,036 --> 00:07:33,955
Out of the question.

74
00:07:35,498 --> 00:07:39,168
Your parents
must be glad I'm gone.

75
00:07:39,335 --> 00:07:40,920
No, they liked you.

76
00:07:41,087 --> 00:07:42,672
I'll bet.

77
00:07:44,423 --> 00:07:46,384
What's that look for?

78
00:07:52,265 --> 00:07:54,225
What's that look for?

79
00:07:54,475 --> 00:07:56,060
Nothing.

80
00:07:56,811 --> 00:07:59,689
Let's not start quarreling again.

81
00:08:00,982 --> 00:08:02,817
How about a game?

82
00:08:02,984 --> 00:08:04,485
Sure.

83
00:08:09,031 --> 00:08:11,200
Got a coin?
I only have one.

84
00:08:11,367 --> 00:08:12,994
Yes, I do.

85
00:08:34,223 --> 00:08:36,100
You go first.

86
00:08:57,079 --> 00:09:00,958
I'm suddenly thinking of those essays
my dad's students write.

87
00:09:01,125 --> 00:09:02,543
What about them?

88
00:09:02,710 --> 00:09:06,714
He read us some great ones
last night over dinner.

89
00:09:07,048 --> 00:09:11,344
They're just kids. They had
to describe their favorite animals.

90
00:09:12,053 --> 00:09:14,847
One little girl of eight
chose a bird.

91
00:09:15,973 --> 00:09:17,725
How did it go?

92
00:09:17,892 --> 00:09:21,020
"A bird is an animal
with an inside and an outside.

93
00:09:21,187 --> 00:09:23,522
Take away the outside
and the inside is left.

94
00:09:23,689 --> 00:09:27,276
Take away the inside
and you see its soul."

95
00:09:37,912 --> 00:09:45,127
THE RECORD SHOP — 2,000 FRANCS —
NANA LIVES HER LIFE

96
00:09:54,512 --> 00:09:56,597
No, we're out of that, sir.

97
00:10:02,103 --> 00:10:03,896
What about Judy Garland?

98
00:10:05,773 --> 00:10:07,942
We don't have her either.

99
00:10:11,028 --> 00:10:15,616
Do you have a guitar recording
by Roméo —

100
00:10:16,617 --> 00:10:19,495
What's his name?
Rafael Romero.

101
00:10:21,038 --> 00:10:22,540
I'll ask.

102
00:10:25,876 --> 00:10:28,045
Rafael Romero on guitar.

103
00:10:28,170 --> 00:10:30,548
In the bins in back.

104
00:10:56,991 --> 00:10:58,701
Is Rita still sick?

105
00:10:58,868 --> 00:11:01,495
Yes. I think she'll be back
Thursday.

106
00:11:01,662 --> 00:11:03,998
What a drag.
She owes me 2,000 francs.

107
00:11:08,294 --> 00:11:11,964
- Can you lend me 2,000?
- You crazy? I'm broke.

108
00:11:12,923 --> 00:11:16,093
Why? Anything wrong?
- No, nothing.

109
00:11:16,260 --> 00:11:17,678
Here it is.

110
00:11:18,429 --> 00:11:20,389
I'll take this too.

111
00:11:39,658 --> 00:11:41,410
This way, sir.

112
00:12:23,077 --> 00:12:25,037
That looks great.

113
00:12:25,162 --> 00:12:28,958
The story's stupid,
but it's very well written.

114
00:12:29,875 --> 00:12:33,462
"He gazed at the turquoise,
star-laden sky

115
00:12:33,629 --> 00:12:35,589
and then turned to me.

116
00:12:35,756 --> 00:12:39,051
'You live your life intensely,
so logically —'

117
00:12:39,218 --> 00:12:40,719
I interrupted him.

118
00:12:40,886 --> 00:12:43,931
'You attach
too much importance to logic.'

119
00:12:44,098 --> 00:12:49,145
For a few seconds I was filled
with a bitter sense of triumph.

120
00:12:49,311 --> 00:12:52,940
No more broken heart,
no more struggle to live again.

121
00:12:53,065 --> 00:12:56,986
No probing questions to face
while masking one's defeat.

122
00:12:57,153 --> 00:13:00,865
Yes, a truly elegant way
of breaking this deadlock."

123
00:13:09,748 --> 00:13:12,751
THE CONCIERGE — PAUL —

124
00:13:12,918 --> 00:13:16,422
<i>THE PASSION OF JOAN OF ARC —</i>
A JOURNALIST

125
00:13:42,531 --> 00:13:44,575
Please give me my key.

126
00:13:45,993 --> 00:13:47,703
All right, then.

127
00:13:51,665 --> 00:13:54,001
Arthur! Get her!

128
00:13:58,172 --> 00:14:00,382
Come on, give me the key.

129
00:14:06,180 --> 00:14:07,681
Here, honey.

130
00:14:12,478 --> 00:14:13,687
Hi.

131
00:14:14,688 --> 00:14:16,106
Where are you headed?

132
00:14:16,273 --> 00:14:18,275
Want to see the pictures?

133
00:14:26,534 --> 00:14:30,538
He doesn't look like me at all.
He looks more like you.

134
00:14:31,497 --> 00:14:33,040
Come have dinner?

135
00:14:34,375 --> 00:14:37,586
- Where are you going?
- Boulevard Saint-Michel.

136
00:14:37,711 --> 00:14:40,339
- Come have dinner.
- I'm not hungry.

137
00:14:40,506 --> 00:14:43,175
I want to see a movie.
Bye.

138
00:14:46,971 --> 00:14:49,265
JOAN OF ARC

139
00:15:19,628 --> 00:15:23,716
We have come
to prepare you for death!

140
00:15:37,021 --> 00:15:39,440
Now... already?

141
00:15:49,783 --> 00:15:51,285
How am I to die?

142
00:15:56,332 --> 00:15:57,833
At the stake!

143
00:16:10,929 --> 00:16:15,976
How can you still believe
you were sent by God?

144
00:16:20,856 --> 00:16:26,695
God knows our path, but we understand it
only at the end of the road!

145
00:16:38,040 --> 00:16:40,042
Yes, I am his child!

146
00:16:50,010 --> 00:16:52,012
And the great victory?

147
00:16:59,228 --> 00:17:01,563
It will be my martyrdom!

148
00:17:02,856 --> 00:17:03,857
And your deliverance?

149
00:17:13,992 --> 00:17:15,369
Death!

150
00:17:30,467 --> 00:17:32,261
Death.

151
00:17:41,478 --> 00:17:43,480
I said good-bye already.

152
00:17:43,647 --> 00:17:45,441
I paid for your movie ticket.

153
00:17:45,607 --> 00:17:47,276
Too bad.

154
00:17:56,744 --> 00:17:58,746
Evening. How are you?

155
00:17:58,912 --> 00:18:00,581
Evening. How are things?

156
00:18:00,914 --> 00:18:03,834
- Didn't we have a date tonight?
- Yes.

157
00:18:04,334 --> 00:18:07,671
I wondered if you were coming.
- Why? Am I late?

158
00:18:07,838 --> 00:18:11,592
Just a bit.
But that's not why I wondered.

159
00:18:12,009 --> 00:18:14,762
I'm usually very punctual.

160
00:18:16,263 --> 00:18:18,640
11:00 p.m. is very late.

161
00:18:23,353 --> 00:18:25,898
I thought you'd forgotten too.

162
00:18:27,149 --> 00:18:28,650
What will you have?

163
00:18:28,817 --> 00:18:31,320
- Any rolls left?
- Sorry, no.

164
00:18:31,487 --> 00:18:33,280
A coffee, then.

165
00:18:35,908 --> 00:18:38,744
Was that a friend outside?

166
00:18:38,994 --> 00:18:41,121
No, it was my brother.

167
00:18:41,830 --> 00:18:43,874
You have lots
of brothers and sisters?

168
00:18:44,041 --> 00:18:46,919
Five brothers and three sisters.

169
00:18:47,586 --> 00:18:50,255
Surprised? It's true.

170
00:18:52,925 --> 00:18:55,302
What's new since Wednesday?

171
00:18:55,969 --> 00:18:58,013
Nothing much.

172
00:18:59,014 --> 00:19:01,725
Is that red car outside yours?

173
00:19:02,601 --> 00:19:04,812
What is it? A Jaguar?

174
00:19:04,978 --> 00:19:09,483
No, an Alfa Romeo.
Are you interested in cars?

175
00:19:09,650 --> 00:19:12,820
No, I don't know
a thing about them.

176
00:19:14,404 --> 00:19:17,825
When shall we take
those pictures?

177
00:19:18,408 --> 00:19:21,995
You tell me.
I already told you I'm ready.

178
00:19:22,538 --> 00:19:24,748
But I'm only free on Sundays.

179
00:19:25,999 --> 00:19:28,627
I'm off to London on Sunday.

180
00:19:28,961 --> 00:19:31,046
Well then, I don't know.

181
00:19:33,549 --> 00:19:36,844
How about now?
Are you tired?

182
00:19:37,678 --> 00:19:41,390
If I say no,
you won't think I'm awful?

183
00:19:41,557 --> 00:19:43,600
Not at all.

184
00:19:45,477 --> 00:19:48,605
Do you really think
I could get into films?

185
00:19:48,772 --> 00:19:50,232
I think so.

186
00:19:50,399 --> 00:19:53,527
Look, I brought you
a composite sheet.

187
00:20:03,203 --> 00:20:05,789
I'd like to do
something like that.

188
00:20:07,708 --> 00:20:09,209
What's this for?

189
00:20:09,376 --> 00:20:12,921
You send it out
to people in films,

190
00:20:13,547 --> 00:20:16,884
and a few days later
maybe they call you.

191
00:20:19,177 --> 00:20:21,847
I'm a bit shy
about undressing.

192
00:20:22,014 --> 00:20:24,600
Just a little.
What can it hurt?

193
00:20:26,768 --> 00:20:29,605
Could you lend me 2,000 francs?

194
00:20:29,771 --> 00:20:32,065
I would, but I haven't got it.

195
00:20:33,734 --> 00:20:35,527
I'm tired.

196
00:20:40,741 --> 00:20:42,534
What about my pictures?

197
00:20:43,201 --> 00:20:45,537
You'll come with me then?

198
00:21:01,011 --> 00:21:08,936
THE POLICE —
NANA IS QUESTIONED

199
00:21:12,522 --> 00:21:15,359
<i>Nana Klein-what?</i>

200
00:21:16,318 --> 00:21:21,323
K-L-E-I-N...

201
00:21:22,449 --> 00:21:28,497
F-R-A-N-K-E-N...

202
00:21:28,664 --> 00:21:31,625
H-E-I-M.

203
00:21:33,126 --> 00:21:38,340
<i>Born April 15th, 1940,
at Flexburg, Moselle.</i>

204
00:21:38,507 --> 00:21:41,218
<i>No fixed address.
Is that right?</i>

205
00:21:41,677 --> 00:21:43,136
Yes.

206
00:21:43,637 --> 00:21:45,806
<i>All right. What happened?</i>

207
00:21:46,223 --> 00:21:49,977
Well, I was walking
down the street,

208
00:21:50,143 --> 00:21:53,063
and I saw a woman
buying a magazine.

209
00:21:53,480 --> 00:21:58,568
Then... she took some money
out of her bag.

210
00:21:59,778 --> 00:22:02,990
She didn't notice
she'd dropped 1,000 francs.

211
00:22:03,949 --> 00:22:09,663
So then... I pretended
to buy a magazine too,

212
00:22:10,122 --> 00:22:13,500
and I put my foot
on her 1,000 francs.

213
00:22:15,585 --> 00:22:18,338
She left and —

214
00:22:24,845 --> 00:22:27,222
And she realized it?

215
00:22:38,191 --> 00:22:40,527
She walked back toward me...

216
00:22:41,570 --> 00:22:44,364
and stared into my eyes
for a long time.

217
00:22:46,199 --> 00:22:50,412
So I gave her back her money.

218
00:22:59,046 --> 00:23:01,381
Then why did she bring charges?

219
00:23:01,840 --> 00:23:05,677
I don't know.
I think it was very mean of her.

220
00:23:14,352 --> 00:23:17,314
Don't you have anyone
you can stay with in Paris?

221
00:23:18,356 --> 00:23:20,442
Friends, sometimes.

222
00:23:21,568 --> 00:23:23,278
Boys?

223
00:23:26,281 --> 00:23:28,033
Sometimes.

224
00:23:32,079 --> 00:23:34,706
Why not ask
for an advance at work?

225
00:23:35,832 --> 00:23:38,418
I already have, too many times.

226
00:23:41,088 --> 00:23:43,381
What are you going to do?

227
00:23:43,715 --> 00:23:45,383
I don't know.

228
00:23:45,634 --> 00:23:47,302
I...

229
00:23:48,428 --> 00:23:50,847
I... is someone else.

230
00:23:56,061 --> 00:24:02,943
THE BOULEVARDS —
THE FIRST MAN — THE ROOM

231
00:25:09,009 --> 00:25:10,719
How about it?

232
00:25:22,564 --> 00:25:24,482
Is this the place?

233
00:25:25,108 --> 00:25:27,235
You've been here before?

234
00:25:28,069 --> 00:25:29,905
Yes, it is.

235
00:25:45,879 --> 00:25:47,589
Anyone there?

236
00:25:47,797 --> 00:25:49,883
<i>You want Room 27 or 28?</i>

237
00:25:52,177 --> 00:25:53,553
Room 27.

238
00:27:07,919 --> 00:27:10,463
- Do you smoke?
- No, thanks.

239
00:27:15,927 --> 00:27:17,929
There's never an ashtray.

240
00:27:19,931 --> 00:27:21,725
Here's one.

241
00:27:33,945 --> 00:27:35,864
How much do you want?

242
00:27:37,449 --> 00:27:40,160
I don't know.
It's up to you.

243
00:27:42,996 --> 00:27:44,873
I don't know.

244
00:27:46,249 --> 00:27:48,001
Four thousand francs?

245
00:28:05,977 --> 00:28:07,854
You owe me 1,000.

246
00:28:08,021 --> 00:28:09,814
I have no change.

247
00:28:10,732 --> 00:28:13,443
Keep it.
It doesn't matter.

248
00:28:13,610 --> 00:28:16,571
It's true.
I'm not just trying to get more.

249
00:28:17,364 --> 00:28:19,741
But you have
to take everything off.

250
00:28:28,666 --> 00:28:30,752
Why not on the mouth?

251
00:28:41,304 --> 00:28:44,599
MEETING YVETTE —
A CAFÉ IN THE SUBURBS —

252
00:28:44,766 --> 00:28:48,228
RAOUL —
GUNSHOTS IN THE STREET

253
00:29:04,452 --> 00:29:06,496
Yvette! How are you?

254
00:29:06,621 --> 00:29:09,499
Is that you? You cut your hair!
- A long time ago.

255
00:29:09,624 --> 00:29:11,084
- How are you?
- And you?

256
00:29:11,251 --> 00:29:13,545
- Oh, I'm getting by.
- Me too.

257
00:29:13,711 --> 00:29:14,754
Good for you.

258
00:29:14,921 --> 00:29:17,674
- Why?
- I thought that —

259
00:29:18,216 --> 00:29:21,177
What are you doing here?

260
00:29:21,344 --> 00:29:23,388
I'm thirsty.
Shall we get a drink?

261
00:29:23,555 --> 00:29:25,014
I'd love to.

262
00:29:26,599 --> 00:29:28,059
How's Raymond?

