00:50:41,707 --> 00:50:43,959
- Is Luigi here?
- Upstairs.

505
00:50:46,878 --> 00:50:48,380
I'll be five minutes.

506
00:50:48,547 --> 00:50:50,882
The movie already started anyway.

507
00:50:53,385 --> 00:50:55,011
A white wine.

508
00:51:07,899 --> 00:51:09,609
Got any Gauloises?

509
00:51:28,170 --> 00:51:30,922
- You have cigarettes?
- Yes. What kind?

510
00:51:31,089 --> 00:51:33,091
I was just wondering.

511
00:52:22,182 --> 00:52:25,393
- Got any cigarettes?
- They've got some downstairs.

512
00:52:33,902 --> 00:52:36,321
- How are you?
- So-so.

513
00:52:36,947 --> 00:52:38,490
What's wrong with her?

514
00:52:38,657 --> 00:52:40,826
We were supposed
to see a movie.

515
00:52:40,992 --> 00:52:42,828
I'll cheer you up.

516
00:52:52,462 --> 00:52:55,715
I'll do the kid
blowing up a balloon.

517
00:53:05,016 --> 00:53:08,520
He's got a balloon,
and he blows it up.

518
00:53:52,731 --> 00:53:55,317
You ought to be my man.

519
00:53:55,567 --> 00:53:57,944
Happy now?
Will you let us talk?

520
00:57:31,950 --> 00:57:39,950
THE STREETS — A GUY —
HAPPINESS IS NO FUN

521
00:58:21,833 --> 00:58:25,086
Did you see Inspector Fleytoux?
He bought a BMW.

522
00:58:57,577 --> 00:58:59,787
They could have provided chairs.

523
00:58:59,954 --> 00:59:02,040
It's always like that.

524
00:59:09,422 --> 00:59:10,757
How much?

525
00:59:10,924 --> 00:59:13,676
3,000.
5,000 if I undress.

526
00:59:15,637 --> 00:59:19,515
Can't you give me one more?
- I have to keep some.

527
00:59:20,642 --> 00:59:22,560
- One of these, then?
- It's all I've got.

528
00:59:22,727 --> 00:59:25,647
A little one.
It would be so nice.

529
00:59:28,733 --> 00:59:30,526
You come here often?

530
00:59:32,904 --> 00:59:35,114
But I've seen you before,
haven't I?

531
00:59:35,323 --> 00:59:36,824
Maybe.

532
00:59:40,078 --> 00:59:42,038
What's your name?

533
00:59:42,205 --> 00:59:43,831
Dimitri.

534
00:59:45,083 --> 00:59:46,709
Nice name.

535
00:59:49,128 --> 00:59:51,464
Yes, I'm fond of it.

536
00:59:52,090 --> 00:59:54,092
What line of work are you in?

537
00:59:54,259 --> 00:59:57,095
I shoot pictures for ads.

538
00:59:57,262 --> 00:59:59,138
You mean like in the movies?

539
00:59:59,305 --> 01:00:01,266
No, still pictures.

540
01:00:02,100 --> 01:00:05,061
I was in a movie with
Eddie Constantine two months ago.

541
01:00:05,270 --> 01:00:08,147
<i>No Pity.</i>
Did you see it?

542
01:00:12,527 --> 01:00:16,447
You don't say much.
Are you the romantic type?

543
01:00:22,370 --> 01:00:25,290
If you give me more,
you can stay.

544
01:00:30,670 --> 01:00:32,880
That's what you want?

545
01:00:34,090 --> 01:00:35,717
I'll go see.

546
01:00:43,975 --> 01:00:45,601
Never mind.

547
01:00:54,610 --> 01:00:56,654
- Are you leaving?
- Yes.

548
01:00:58,614 --> 01:01:02,493
- Can you spare five minutes?
- Ask Monique. She's in 41.

549
01:01:15,048 --> 01:01:17,800
- What's up?
- Nothing.

550
01:01:20,803 --> 01:01:23,014
The elevators never work.

551
01:01:24,474 --> 01:01:27,018
See you Tuesday
at the Olympia.

552
01:01:42,033 --> 01:01:43,826
- What are you doing?
- Going downstairs.

553
01:01:43,993 --> 01:01:46,871
- Can you spare a moment?
- How much?

554
01:01:47,038 --> 01:01:49,665
I don't know.
We can discuss it.

555
01:01:49,874 --> 01:01:51,334
All right.

556
01:01:51,459 --> 01:01:53,503
Room 45.

557
01:02:14,899 --> 01:02:17,193
Work it out with her.

558
01:02:23,658 --> 01:02:26,160
- All right?
- Yes.

559
01:02:32,083 --> 01:02:35,670
- What's your name?
- Elizabeth. Like the Queen of England.

560
01:02:38,631 --> 01:02:40,883
Shall I strip too?

561
01:02:41,050 --> 01:02:42,802
Actually, don't bother.

562
01:02:42,969 --> 01:02:45,221
So you don't need me anymore?

563
01:02:45,680 --> 01:02:47,348
I don't know.

564
01:02:56,566 --> 01:02:58,276
Like that.

565
01:03:12,290 --> 01:03:19,297
PLACE DU CHÂTELET — A STRANGER —
NANA, THE UNWITTING PHILOSOPHER

566
01:04:30,952 --> 01:04:33,371
Do you mind me looking?

567
01:04:36,707 --> 01:04:38,543
You look bored.

568
01:04:38,709 --> 01:04:40,169
<i>Not at all.</i>

569
01:04:42,505 --> 01:04:45,174
- What are you doing?
<i>- Reading.</i>

570
01:04:54,850 --> 01:04:56,811
Will you buy me a drink?

571
01:04:57,562 --> 01:04:59,272
<i>If you like.</i>

572
01:05:06,112 --> 01:05:07,989
Do you come here often?

573
01:05:08,155 --> 01:05:11,158
Occasionally.
Today I just happened by.

574
01:05:12,994 --> 01:05:14,996
Why are you reading?

575
01:05:15,162 --> 01:05:16,831
It's my job.

576
01:05:22,962 --> 01:05:24,922
It's funny.

577
01:05:25,047 --> 01:05:27,091
Suddenly I don't know what to say.

578
01:05:27,967 --> 01:05:30,011
It happens to me a lot.

579
01:05:30,469 --> 01:05:32,513
I know what I want to say.

580
01:05:32,680 --> 01:05:36,892
I think first about whether
they're the right words.

581
01:05:37,351 --> 01:05:42,231
But when the moment comes
to speak, I can't say it.

582
01:05:42,398 --> 01:05:44,775
Yes, of course.

583
01:05:45,443 --> 01:05:47,778
Have you read
<i>The Three Musketeers?</i>

584
01:05:47,945 --> 01:05:51,198
No, but I saw the movie. Why?

585
01:05:53,075 --> 01:05:57,288
Because in it, Porthos —

586
01:05:58,289 --> 01:06:01,500
Actually, this is from
<i>Twenty Years Later.</i>

587
01:06:01,667 --> 01:06:05,588
Porthos is tall, strong,
and a little dense.

588
01:06:06,589 --> 01:06:09,592
He's never had a thought in his life.

589
01:06:10,509 --> 01:06:15,806
He has to place a bomb
in a cellar to blow it up.

590
01:06:15,973 --> 01:06:17,892
He does it.

591
01:06:18,059 --> 01:06:22,480
He places the bomb, lights the fuse,
and starts to run away.

592
01:06:23,189 --> 01:06:26,108
But just then he begins to think.

593
01:06:27,318 --> 01:06:29,236
About what?

594
01:06:29,403 --> 01:06:33,491
How it's possible to put
one foot in front of the other.

595
01:06:33,658 --> 01:06:36,327
I'm sure that's happened to you.

596
01:06:37,995 --> 01:06:42,416
So he stops running.
He can't move forward.

597
01:06:45,670 --> 01:06:49,173
The bomb explodes,
and the cellar caves in around him.

598
01:06:49,340 --> 01:06:52,510
He holds it up
with his strong shoulders.

599
01:06:52,677 --> 01:06:57,431
But after a day or two,
he's crushed to death.

600
01:06:58,015 --> 01:07:00,601
So the first time he thought,
it killed him.

601
01:07:00,726 --> 01:07:03,479
Why do you tell me
things like that?

602
01:07:04,313 --> 01:07:07,233
No reason. Just to talk.

603
01:07:07,400 --> 01:07:09,902
Why must one always talk?

604
01:07:10,569 --> 01:07:14,782
I think one should often
just keep quiet, live in silence.

605
01:07:16,075 --> 01:07:19,412
The more one talks,
the less the words mean.

606
01:07:19,578 --> 01:07:22,707
Perhaps,
but can one do that?

607
01:07:24,375 --> 01:07:25,376
I don't know.

608
01:07:25,543 --> 01:07:29,296
It's always struck me,
the fact we can't live without speaking.

609
01:07:34,051 --> 01:07:36,804
But it would be nice.

610
01:07:37,388 --> 01:07:40,725
Yes, it would be nice, wouldn't it?

611
01:07:41,726 --> 01:07:44,437
Sort of like we loved
one another more.

612
01:07:44,603 --> 01:07:47,732
But it's impossible.
No one's been able to.

613
01:07:47,857 --> 01:07:49,400
But why?

614
01:07:49,567 --> 01:07:52,737
Words should express
just what one wants to say.

615
01:07:53,404 --> 01:07:55,072
Do they betray us?

616
01:07:56,907 --> 01:07:59,076
Yes, but we betray them too.

617
01:07:59,243 --> 01:08:01,412
One should be able
to express oneself.

618
01:08:01,579 --> 01:08:03,956
We manage
to write things quite well.

619
01:08:04,123 --> 01:08:08,002
It's extraordinary
that someone like Plato

620
01:08:08,169 --> 01:08:12,089
can still be understood.
People really do understand him.

621
01:08:12,256 --> 01:08:16,135
Yet he wrote in Greek
2,500 years ago.

622
01:08:16,302 --> 01:08:21,474
No one really knows
the language, not exactly.

623
01:08:21,807 --> 01:08:26,187
Yet something gets through, so we
should be able to express ourselves.

624
01:08:27,730 --> 01:08:29,774
And we have to.

625
01:08:29,940 --> 01:08:33,944
Why do we have to?
To understand each other?

626
01:08:38,616 --> 01:08:40,618
We must think,

627
01:08:41,118 --> 01:08:43,746
and for thought we need words.

628
01:08:43,913 --> 01:08:46,123
There's no other way to think.

629
01:08:46,290 --> 01:08:49,752
To communicate, one must speak.
That's our life.

630
01:08:49,919 --> 01:08:52,505
Yes, but at the same time,
it's very hard.

631
01:08:56,383 --> 01:08:59,637
Whereas I think
life should be easy.

632
01:09:03,307 --> 01:09:07,812
Your tale about the Three Musketeers
may be a very nice story,

633
01:09:08,187 --> 01:09:09,855
but it's terrible.

634
01:09:10,022 --> 01:09:12,775
Yes, but it's a pointer.

635
01:09:14,068 --> 01:09:15,820
I believe

636
01:09:16,737 --> 01:09:22,326
one learns to speak well only when
one has renounced life for a while.

637
01:09:22,493 --> 01:09:25,496
That's the price.
- So to speak is fatal?

638
01:09:25,621 --> 01:09:30,000
Speaking is almost
a resurrection in relation to life.

639
01:09:30,167 --> 01:09:34,338
Speaking is a different life
from when one does not speak.

640
01:09:34,505 --> 01:09:37,800
So to live speaking,

641
01:09:38,342 --> 01:09:41,971
one must pass through
the death of life without speaking.

642
01:09:42,096 --> 01:09:44,974
I don't know if I'm being clear...

643
01:09:46,517 --> 01:09:51,188
but there's a kind of ascetic rule
that stops one from speaking well

644
01:09:51,814 --> 01:09:55,025
until one sees life with detachment.

645
01:09:57,361 --> 01:10:03,117
But one can't live everyday life
with... I don't know —

646
01:10:04,159 --> 01:10:05,911
Detachment?

647
01:10:06,078 --> 01:10:10,666
We go back and forth. That's why
we pass from silence to words.

648
01:10:11,250 --> 01:10:16,213
We swing between the two,
because it's the movement of life.

649
01:10:16,630 --> 01:10:20,718
From everyday life
one rises to a life —

650
01:10:20,885 --> 01:10:25,431
Let's call it superior — why not?
It's the thinking life.

651
01:10:25,598 --> 01:10:29,518
But the thinking life presupposes
that one has killed off

652
01:10:29,685 --> 01:10:32,813
a life that's too mundane,
too rudimentary.

653
01:10:34,648 --> 01:10:38,444
Then thinking and speaking
are the same thing?

654
01:10:38,736 --> 01:10:40,529
I believe so.

655
01:10:40,696 --> 01:10:44,283
It's in Plato, you know.
It's an old idea.

656
01:10:44,450 --> 01:10:48,245
I don't think
one can distinguish a thought

657
01:10:48,412 --> 01:10:50,873
from the words that express it.

658
01:10:50,998 --> 01:10:57,087
A moment of thought can only
be grasped through words.

659
01:10:57,254 --> 01:10:59,882
So to speak is to risk lying?

660
01:11:00,049 --> 01:11:02,968
Lies too are part of our quest.

661
01:11:03,135 --> 01:11:06,430
There's little difference
between an error and a lie.

662
01:11:06,597 --> 01:11:11,185
I don't mean ordinary lies,
like promising,

663
01:11:11,352 --> 01:11:15,773
"I'll be here tomorrow at 5:00,"
and then not showing up.

664
01:11:15,940 --> 01:11:17,983
Those are just ploys.

665
01:11:18,150 --> 01:11:24,490
But a subtle lie
often differs little from an error.

666
01:11:24,657 --> 01:11:28,619
One's searching for something
and can't find the right word.

667
01:11:28,786 --> 01:11:33,082
That's why you didn't know
what to say before.

668
01:11:33,248 --> 01:11:37,127
I think you were afraid
of not finding the right word.

669
01:11:39,880 --> 01:11:43,384
How can one be sure
of having found the right word?

670
01:11:45,844 --> 01:11:49,556
One must work at it.
It only comes with effort.

671
01:11:49,723 --> 01:11:54,269
To say what must be said
in the appropriate way,

672
01:11:54,395 --> 01:11:56,522
that is, that doesn't hurt,

673
01:11:56,647 --> 01:12:00,109
that says what must be said,
does what must be done,

674
01:12:00,234 --> 01:12:02,778
without hurting
or wounding anyone.

675
01:12:04,321 --> 01:12:07,616
One must try to act in good faith.

676
01:12:09,076 --> 01:12:10,995
Someone once told me,

677
01:12:11,161 --> 01:12:14,999
"There's truth in everything,
even in error."

678
01:12:15,958 --> 01:12:17,251
It's true.

679
01:12:17,418 --> 01:12:21,338
That's what France didn't see
in the 17th century.

680
01:12:21,505 --> 01:12:26,135
They thought one could
avoid errors and lies,

681
01:12:26,301 --> 01:12:29,471
that one could live
directly in the truth.

682
01:12:29,638 --> 01:12:31,348
I don't think it's possible.

683
01:12:31,515 --> 01:12:34,643
Hence Kant, Hegel,
German philosophy:

684
01:12:34,810 --> 01:12:37,604
to bring us back to life

685
01:12:37,771 --> 01:12:42,985
and make us see that we must pass
through error to arrive at truth.

686
01:12:46,530 --> 01:12:48,866
What do you think about love?

687
01:12:51,577 --> 01:12:55,247
The body had to come into it,

688
01:12:55,414 --> 01:12:58,167
and indeed,
Leibniz introduced the contingent.

689
01:12:58,333 --> 01:13:02,713
Contingent truths
and necessary truths make up life.

690
01:13:02,880 --> 01:13:06,884
German philosophy
showed us that in life,

691
01:13:07,051 --> 01:13:11,096
one thinks with the constraints
and errors of life.

692
01:13:11,263 --> 01:13:14,558
One must manage with that.
It's true.

693
01:13:16,685 --> 01:13:20,314
Shouldn't love be the only truth?

694
01:13:22,232 --> 01:13:26,028
But for that,
love would always have to be true.

695
01:13:26,195 --> 01:13:30,240
Do you know anyone who knows
right off what he loves?

696
01:13:31,366 --> 01:13:34,328
No. When you're 20,
you don't know.

697
01:13:34,495 --> 01:13:38,582
All you know are bits and pieces.
You grasp at experience.

698
01:13:38,749 --> 01:13:42,336
At that age, "I love"
is a mixture of many things.

699
01:13:42,503 --> 01:13:48,550
To be completely at one
with what you love takes maturity.

700
01:13:48,717 --> 01:13:50,886
That means searching.

701
01:13:51,053 --> 01:13:53,138
That's the truth of life.

702
01:13:54,723 --> 01:13:57,267
That's why love is a solution,

703
01:13:57,434 --> 01:14:00,646
but on the condition that it be true.

704
01:14:02,481 --> 01:14:10,322
THE YOUNG MAN AGAIN — THE OVAL
PORTRAIT — RAOUL TRADES NANA

705
01:14:20,415 --> 01:14:22,292
What shall we do today?

706
01:14:23,085 --> 01:14:24,378
I don't know.

707
01:14:24,503 --> 01:14:26,797
Shall we go
to the Luxembourg Garden?

708
01:14:29,591 --> 01:14:32,469
I think it's going to rain.

709
01:14:34,513 --> 01:14:38,767
<i>"I thus saw in vivid light
a picture all unnoticed before.</i>

710
01:14:39,726 --> 01:14:43,939
It was the portrait of a young girl
just ripening into womanhood.

711
01:14:44,148 --> 01:14:48,610
I glanced at the painting hurriedly,
and then closed my eyes.

712
01:14:57,494 --> 01:15:01,373
It was an impulsive movement
to gain time for thought,

713
01:15:02,166 --> 01:15:05,210
to make sure that my vision
had not deceived me,

714
01:15:05,377 --> 01:15:10,340
to calm and subdue my fancy
for a more sober and more certain gaze.

715
01:15:11,008 --> 01:15:15,512
In a very few moments
I again looked fixedly at the painting.

716
01:15:21,727 --> 01:15:25,939
The portrait, I have already said,
was that of a young girl.

717
01:15:27,065 --> 01:15:29,943
It was a mere head and shoulders,

718
01:15:30,110 --> 01:15:34,239
done in what is technically
termed a vignette manner,

719
01:15:34,865 --> 01:15:38,702
much in the style
of the favorite heads of Sully.

720
01:15:38,994 --> 01:15:43,207
The arms, the bosom,
and even the ends of the radiant hair

721
01:15:43,373 --> 01:15:47,461
melted imperceptibly
into the vague yet deep shadow

722
01:15:47,628 --> 01:15:49,922
which formed
the background of the whole.

723
01:15:51,089 --> 01:15:54,176
As a thing of art,
nothing could be more admirable

724
01:15:54,343 --> 01:15:56,595
than the painting itself.

725
01:15:57,262 --> 01:16:00,641
But it could have been
neither the execution of the work,

726
01:16:00,807 --> 01:16:02,893
nor the immortal beauty
of the countenance,

727
01:16:03,060 --> 01:16:06,521
which had so suddenly
and so vehemently moved me.

728
01:16:06,688 --> 01:16:11,068
Least of all could it have been that
my fancy, shaken from its half slumber,

729
01:16:11,235 --> 01:16:14,363
had mistaken the head
for that of a living person.

730
01:16:18,242 --> 01:16:22,329
At length, satisfied
with the true secret of its effect,

731
01:16:22,496 --> 01:16:25,082
I fell back within the bed.

732
01:16:25,249 --> 01:16:28,085
I had found the spell of the picture

733
01:16:28,252 --> 01:16:33,423
in an absolute life-likeliness
of expression."

734
01:16:33,757 --> 01:16:35,467
Is that your book?

735
01:16:35,634 --> 01:16:37,636
No, I found it here.

736
01:16:43,809 --> 01:16:45,644
Can I have one?

737
01:16:54,778 --> 01:16:59,366
It's our story:
a painter portraying his love.

738
01:17:00,075 --> 01:17:01,743
Shall I go on?

739
01:17:04,788 --> 01:17:09,001
"And in sooth
some who beheld the portrait

740
01:17:09,126 --> 01:17:12,963
spoke of its resemblance
in low words as of a mighty marvel,

741
01:17:13,130 --> 01:17:16,300
and a proof not less
of the power of the painter

742
01:17:16,466 --> 01:17:20,971
than of his deep love for her
whom he depicted so surpassingly well.

743
01:17:21,221 --> 01:17:25,475
But at length, as the labor drew
nearer to its conclusion,

744
01:17:25,642 --> 01:17:28,145
there were admitted none
into the turret.

745
01:17:28,312 --> 01:17:31,398
For the painter had grown wild
with the ardor of his work,

746
01:17:31,565 --> 01:17:37,029
and turned his eyes from the canvas
rarely, even to regard his wife.

747
01:17:37,321 --> 01:17:41,116
And he would not see that the tints
which he spread upon the canvas

748
01:17:41,283 --> 01:17:45,370
were drawn from the cheeks of her
who sat beside him.

749
01:17:45,829 --> 01:17:50,917
And when many weeks had passed,
and but little remained to do,

750
01:17:51,168 --> 01:17:55,130
save one brush upon the mouth
and one tint upon the eye,

751
01:17:55,297 --> 01:17:59,551
the spirit of the lady again flickered up
as the flame within a lamp.

752
01:18:00,010 --> 01:18:04,389
And then the brush was given,
and then the tint was placed.

753
01:18:05,098 --> 01:18:08,101
And, for one moment,
the painter stood entranced

754
01:18:08,268 --> 01:18:10,771
before the work he had wrought.

755
01:18:10,937 --> 01:18:14,107
But in the next, while he yet gazed,

756
01:18:14,274 --> 01:18:16,985
he grew tremulous and aghast,

757
01:18:17,110 --> 01:18:21,365
and crying with a loud voice,
"This is indeed Life itself!"

758
01:18:21,531 --> 01:18:24,868
turned suddenly to regard his beloved:

759
01:18:25,410 --> 01:18:27,037
She was dead!"

760
01:18:36,171 --> 01:18:38,548
I'd like to go to the Louvre.

761
01:18:38,882 --> 01:18:41,802
No, I don't like looking at pictures.

762
01:18:45,097 --> 01:18:48,475
Why? Art and beauty are life!

763
01:18:52,229 --> 01:18:53,647
I adore you.

764
01:18:54,064 --> 01:18:55,440
And I love you.

765
01:19:03,698 --> 01:19:06,076
Why not come and live with me?

766
01:19:06,535 --> 01:19:08,912
Yes. I'll tell Raoul it's all over.

767
01:19:15,961 --> 01:19:20,215
Let me at least put my coat on
or I'll catch cold!

768
01:19:20,340 --> 01:19:22,300
Stop acting hysterical.

769
01:19:29,683 --> 01:19:31,059
No, Raoul, not now!

770
01:19:31,226 --> 01:19:33,186
Stop acting hysterical!

771
01:19:33,645 --> 01:19:35,564
You know each other?

772
01:19:51,955 --> 01:19:53,957
What did I do wrong?

773
01:19:55,083 --> 01:19:57,169
You must take anyone who pays.

774
01:19:57,335 --> 01:20:00,881
Not anyone.
Sometimes it's degrading.

775
01:20:01,673 --> 01:20:03,800
See? That's where you're wrong.

776
01:20:11,224 --> 01:20:15,479
The movies are a drag.
Weekdays we're too busy,

777
01:20:15,645 --> 01:20:18,148
and on Sundays
there's always a line.

778
01:20:21,234 --> 01:20:24,654
- Where are you going?
- Taking them back to their car.

779
01:20:24,821 --> 01:20:27,324
Why did you make me come?

780
01:20:27,866 --> 01:20:29,868
You're going with them.

781
01:20:31,328 --> 01:20:34,331
HADES AND SONS

782
01:21:37,519 --> 01:21:39,354
Well, are you going?

783
01:21:54,828 --> 01:21:56,580
First the girl.

784
01:22:06,256 --> 01:22:07,757
First the money.

785
01:22:12,387 --> 01:22:14,222
Get the money.

786
01:22:47,297 --> 01:22:49,341
There's 100,000 missing.

787
01:22:49,674 --> 01:22:51,259
Don't move.

788
01:22:51,426 --> 01:22:53,720
Don't think I won't shoot
just because of the girl.

789
01:22:53,887 --> 01:22:55,680
No, don't shoot me!

790
01:22:58,642 --> 01:23:01,436
You shoot.
I forgot to load.

